data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 (.NET 10), new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` is a span-based method that **cannot be represented in an expression tree**. When the expression is compiled with `preferInterpretation: true` (or used in any expression-tree context like EF Core), it throws at runtime because the expression tree interpreter doesn't support span methods.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to resolve `Enumerable.Contains` by making the receiver explicitly `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
